{"key":"post-17097702","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17097702</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Cultivatorian said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Could I use these??&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.grainger.com/Grainger/LAB-SAFETY-SUPPLY-Filter-12K926?Pid=search&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;http://www.grainger.com/Grainger&lt;wbr&gt;/LAB-SAFETY-SUPPLY-Filter-12K926?&lt;wbr&gt;Pid=search&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Not suitable.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;First, they're paper.&amp;nbsp; That means they start to degrade when damp, which is going to happen in the pressure cooker.&amp;nbsp; Second, they are also not temperature rated, which means the pore size changes during sterilization.&amp;nbsp; Third, they will allow the mycelium to colonize them since they're not synthetic.&amp;nbsp; Fourth, they are thin and will have the same problems as the filters on unicorn bags, which have an almost 100% failure rate due to faulty filters.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Synthetic filter disks are nearly 1/8&quot; thick, are synthetic so they don't degrade, and are heat resistant.&amp;nbsp; They also can be had for less than 40 cents each, so I fail to see how that's so expensive considering they can be used and reused thousands of times.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17097760</next>\n<prev>17097701</prev>\n<first>17097542</first>\n<last>17114263</last>\n<when>1351175634</when>\n<utime>10/25/12 05:33 PM</utime>\n</post>"}